          "id": "medmcqa-91e55f8d-64ca-4d92-aa4e-52772b08fd91",
          "text": "Most common cause of fetal ventriculomegaly is?",
          "options": [
            {
              "id": "opt-1",
              "text": "Arnold Chiari malformation -I"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-2",
              "text": "Arnold Chiari malformation -II"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-3",
              "text": "Aqueductal stenosis"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-4",
              "text": "Dandy Walker malformation"
            }
          ],
          "correctOptionId": "opt-2",
          "explanation": "Ans. is 'c' i.e., Aqueductal stenosis Hydrocephalus is characterized by an increased CSF volume with progressive ventricular dilatation (ventriculomegaly). o Obstructive or noncommunicating hydrocephalus/ventriculomegaly develops most commonly in children because of an abnormality of the aqueduct or a lesion in the 4' ventricle. o Obstruction of the aqueduct is the single most common cause of fetal and neonatal hydrocephalus/ ventriculomegaly. o Nonobstructive or communicating hydrocephalus most commonly follows a subarachnoid hemorrhage, which is usually a result of intraventricular hemorrhage in a premature infant."
