          "correctOptionId": "opt-1",
          "explanation": "Ans. is 'b' i.e., Toxoplasmosis o This question is straight forward; spiramycin is in pregnancy is given for toxoplasmosis. Prenatally acquired T.gondii may infect the brain and retina of the fetus and can cause chorioretinitis, intracerebral calcifications, and hydrocephalus. o Cerebral calcification and hydrocephalus may also occur with congenital CMV and HSV infection, but spiramycin is not given for these infections. Feature Toxoplasmosis CAW HSV Rubella Hydrocephalus -H- +/? (Rare) Microcephaly ++ -H? Intracranial ++ +\\\\? Calcification (Common) (Common) (Uncommon) (Rare)"
