        {
          "id": "medmcqa-23b52b4a-3b1e-4fd4-8676-7142d9fbb7c4",
          "text": "The renal biopsy of a 6–year–old boy with recurrent gross hematuria shows IgA nephropathy. The urinary protein excretion is 130 mg/day. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management –",
          "options": [
            {
              "id": "opt-1",
              "text": "Administer corticosteroids"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-2",
              "text": "Give Azathiopiine"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-3",
              "text": "Start Cyclosporine"
            },
            {
              "id": "opt-4",
              "text": "Urinary bag sample"
            }
          ],
          "correctOptionId": "opt-1",
          "explanation": "T/T of IgA nephropathy\n\nThere is no proven tit for IgA nephropathy.\nThe primary t/t is proper blood pressure control.\n\nThe drugs which have been proved useful are:-\ni)  Fish oil (It contains omega - 3 fatty acids).\n\nIt is an anti-inflammatory agent and it prevents the rate of renal progression.\n\nii)   Immunosuppressive therapy -\n\nIt is done with corticosteroids with or without cytotoxic therapy.\n\niii) ACE inhibitors and Angiotensin II receptor antagonists -\n\nTheir role in reducing proteinuria and retarding the rate of renal progression is still to be determined.\n\niv) Prophylactic antibiotics and tonsillectomy -\n\nIt may reduce the frequency of gross hematuria but they have no effect on the progression of renal disease."
        }
